WEBVTT

00:00.709 --> 00:02.920
[♪♪♪]

00:15.349 --> 00:17.601
Good morning,
Mrs. Thornton.

00:17.601 --> 00:20.061
Good morning,
Mr. Thornton.

00:20.061 --> 00:21.772
You're going to
spoil me.

00:22.898 --> 00:24.984
I'm gonna try.

00:27.068 --> 00:28.737
Mmm.

00:30.948 --> 00:32.867
[SIGHS]

00:35.828 --> 00:37.162
I made eggs.

00:37.162 --> 00:39.540
I know you like 'em
sunny-side up,

00:39.540 --> 00:40.833
but I broke a few.

00:40.833 --> 00:42.918
I'm sure I will love
whatever you make.

00:43.836 --> 00:45.295
Good.

00:45.295 --> 00:47.715
Good, because
I burned the bacon.

00:47.715 --> 00:49.466
[BOTH LAUGH]

00:49.466 --> 00:50.926
Oh, so I checked,
and the Cubs

00:50.926 --> 00:53.094
are gonna be in town
during our honeymoon.

00:53.094 --> 00:54.513
Oh, that's great.

00:54.513 --> 00:56.807
We'll definitely have
to take in a game there.

00:56.807 --> 00:58.058
I can't wait.

00:58.058 --> 00:59.935
A whole week
in Chicago with you.

00:59.935 --> 01:01.812
It's gonna be
a trip to remember.

01:02.730 --> 01:04.481
[SIGHS]

01:04.481 --> 01:05.524
Enjoy.

01:05.524 --> 01:06.817
Mm.

01:06.817 --> 01:08.903
[♪♪♪]

01:08.903 --> 01:10.821
You know what?

01:10.821 --> 01:13.949
Maybe I should spoil you
with breakfast tomorrow.

01:17.202 --> 01:19.246
[BOTH LAUGHING]

01:23.500 --> 01:24.835
Here you go.

01:24.835 --> 01:27.337
Fresh, piping-hot.
Mm.

01:27.337 --> 01:28.839
Today's the day
we set up

01:28.839 --> 01:30.925
the donation tables
outside the mercantile.

01:30.925 --> 01:32.593
I hope the weather
holds up.

01:32.593 --> 01:34.093
Mm-hmm.

01:34.093 --> 01:36.346
You know, the bank closure
really has had

01:36.346 --> 01:38.766
a terrible impact
on the town.

01:38.766 --> 01:40.434
With no cash
to buy things,

01:40.434 --> 01:42.352
families are really
feeling the pinch.

01:42.352 --> 01:43.645
Yeah.

01:43.645 --> 01:45.564
[♪♪♪]

01:45.564 --> 01:46.857
So...

01:46.857 --> 01:48.525
I went through your things.

01:48.525 --> 01:51.403
I thought you could spare
your old blue striped shirt...

01:51.403 --> 01:53.030
Mm-hmm.

01:55.616 --> 01:57.284
And your green plaid pants.

01:59.244 --> 02:00.537
No. No, no, no, no.

02:00.537 --> 02:02.163
I love
the green plaid pants.

02:02.163 --> 02:03.582
Oh, so you were
listening.

02:03.582 --> 02:05.918
Sweetheart,
I am always listening.

02:05.918 --> 02:07.168
Really?
Mm-hmm.

02:07.168 --> 02:08.754
What time did I say
we're invited

02:08.754 --> 02:10.631
to Jack and Elizabeth's
for dinner?

02:12.299 --> 02:14.593
Um...6.

02:15.719 --> 02:17.554
I mean...7.

02:19.014 --> 02:20.015
Eight?

02:20.015 --> 02:21.809
Lee...

02:21.809 --> 02:24.103
Didn't say anything about
Jack or Elizabeth.

02:24.103 --> 02:25.646
You tricked me.

02:26.772 --> 02:28.690
Fine. You can have
the gray twills,

02:28.690 --> 02:31.026
but I wanna keep
the plaid.

02:31.026 --> 02:32.903
I was kidding
about the pants.

02:32.903 --> 02:34.696
The donation table
is only for items

02:34.696 --> 02:35.990
people can actually use.

02:37.032 --> 02:39.534
[SIGHS]
Ouch.

02:43.371 --> 02:45.749
Pastor Frank, I think
I saw some fish over there.

02:45.749 --> 02:47.208
Well, you better
go get 'em.

02:47.208 --> 02:49.461
Okay.

02:49.461 --> 02:51.755
I missed this.

02:52.923 --> 02:55.425
Have you heard from
Children's Hospital?

02:55.425 --> 02:57.218
Not yet.

02:57.218 --> 02:58.595
They said
they'd let me know

02:58.595 --> 03:00.597
when they find
a replacement.

03:02.181 --> 03:04.476
Tell me about
the people there.

03:04.476 --> 03:06.687
[♪♪♪]

03:08.396 --> 03:11.608
There was this one boy--
Good kid--

03:11.608 --> 03:13.861
Kinda reminded me
of Cody.

03:14.862 --> 03:17.196
His name was Anthony.

03:18.907 --> 03:21.242
He had pneumonia.

03:21.242 --> 03:23.537
Doctors didn't have
much hope for him.

03:23.537 --> 03:26.540
They gave him
two weeks to live.

03:28.500 --> 03:31.378
I used to sit and read with him
every morning.

03:31.378 --> 03:33.005
Sometimes scripture.

03:33.005 --> 03:34.548
Mostly Peter Pan.

03:34.548 --> 03:36.925
[CHUCKLES]

03:36.925 --> 03:39.386
What happened to him?

03:39.386 --> 03:42.097
Well, it was a long road,
but he made a full recovery.

03:42.097 --> 03:45.642
Yeah, he marched himself
right out of that hospital.

03:45.642 --> 03:48.228
The doctors
couldn't understand it.

03:51.773 --> 03:53.067
But you could.

03:53.067 --> 03:56.695
Survival requires
a strength of will.

03:56.695 --> 03:59.280
Anthony wouldn't give up.

04:01.116 --> 04:02.367
I wouldn't let him.

04:05.662 --> 04:08.207
He was lucky
he had you there.

04:14.171 --> 04:16.381
[♪♪♪]

04:34.191 --> 04:35.901
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

04:35.901 --> 04:38.695
Good morning,
lovebirds.

04:38.695 --> 04:41.156
Are you awake?
Come on in, Rosemary.

04:41.156 --> 04:43.784
Is Jack still here?
He's upstairs.

04:43.784 --> 04:46.203
So? How are the newlyweds?

04:46.203 --> 04:49.164
Need I even ask? I'm sure the
two of you are over the moon.

04:49.164 --> 04:50.832
[CHUCKLES]
We are, thank you.

04:50.832 --> 04:53.460
If you're looking for the box
of clothes, it's there.

04:53.460 --> 04:55.045
Everyone has
been so generous.

04:55.045 --> 04:57.422
A lot of people are going
to benefit from this.

04:57.422 --> 05:00.634
Oh! My...

05:00.634 --> 05:03.137
[CHUCKLES]
Why, look at that.

05:03.137 --> 05:06.807
[CHUCKLES]
That was Jack.

05:06.807 --> 05:08.308
It's very romantic.

05:08.308 --> 05:10.978
Hmm. He is all that,
and more.

05:12.813 --> 05:13.814
Oh.

05:13.814 --> 05:15.107
[GASPS]

05:15.107 --> 05:17.109
[BOTH LAUGH]

05:17.109 --> 05:18.777
That's very sweet.

05:18.777 --> 05:21.529
Jack and I have been
writing each other notes.

05:21.529 --> 05:24.324
This one is for him to meet me
at Abigail's cafe later.

05:24.324 --> 05:25.951
I have a surprise for him.

05:25.951 --> 05:28.829
Oh. Wedded bliss...

05:28.829 --> 05:32.874
[SIGHS]
Mm, there's nothing
quite like it.

05:32.874 --> 05:34.042
[CHUCKLES]

05:34.042 --> 05:35.627
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

05:35.627 --> 05:37.045
Well, that coat
looks nice.

05:37.045 --> 05:39.006
It's a little long.

05:39.006 --> 05:40.882
And there's a hole
in the pocket.

05:40.882 --> 05:43.010
Well, you can sew it.

05:43.635 --> 05:45.595
There we go.

05:47.306 --> 05:50.017
I'm so pleased.
Look at the turnout.

05:50.017 --> 05:51.392
It's a great turnout.

05:51.392 --> 05:52.894
Anyway, I got
to get to work.

05:52.894 --> 05:54.353
Mmm. Bye.

05:54.353 --> 05:56.231
[♪♪♪]

05:57.191 --> 05:59.193
How are you doing?
Good.

06:00.944 --> 06:03.697
Anyway, I've got to go.
Okay.

06:10.996 --> 06:12.914
Lee!

06:12.914 --> 06:14.875
I'll walk you to work.

06:28.471 --> 06:30.515
[CHILDREN PLAYING]

06:30.515 --> 06:32.726
[♪♪♪]

06:34.393 --> 06:36.771
You got it, Philip!

06:37.689 --> 06:38.940
What happened?

06:38.940 --> 06:40.984
I'm sorry.
The sun was in my eyes.

06:43.153 --> 06:44.487
What sun?

06:44.487 --> 06:46.156
I'm sorry.
I couldn't see the ball.

06:46.156 --> 06:48.325
What do you mean?
It was coming right at you.

06:48.325 --> 06:51.578
[♪♪♪]

06:51.578 --> 06:53.247
[CLANGING]

06:53.247 --> 06:55.957
ELIZABETH:
Time for class, everyone.

07:00.545 --> 07:02.672
I can't believe you didn't
catch the ball.

07:02.672 --> 07:04.632
I said I was sorry!
Okay, Anna, enough.

07:04.632 --> 07:06.425
Everyone misses
the ball now and again.

07:06.425 --> 07:08.095
PHILIP:
I'm sorry,
Mrs. Thornton.

07:08.095 --> 07:10.013
Don't worry, Philip.
It's only a game.

07:10.013 --> 07:11.348
I made a big mistake.

07:11.348 --> 07:12.599
Everyone makes mistakes.

07:12.599 --> 07:14.559
Besides, you'll catch
the next pop fly,

07:14.559 --> 07:16.144
then no one will
remember this.

07:16.144 --> 07:18.063
Run along.

07:19.231 --> 07:20.857
Morning.

07:20.857 --> 07:23.068
[♪♪♪]

07:27.030 --> 07:28.907
[CHUCKLES]

07:35.789 --> 07:37.707
[CHUCKLES]

07:46.216 --> 07:47.801
[KISSES]

07:50.178 --> 07:51.930
[CHUCKLES]
[DOOR OPENS]

07:51.930 --> 07:53.890
[GASPS]

07:53.890 --> 07:54.975
Well, hello!

07:54.975 --> 07:57.269
What is all this?

07:57.269 --> 08:00.314
I brought you
a nice, hot lunch.

08:00.314 --> 08:01.689
A titan of industry

08:01.689 --> 08:03.400
can't run on
an empty stomach.

08:03.400 --> 08:05.526
I was gonna grab
something from the saloon.

08:05.526 --> 08:07.070
Or more likely
get busy working

08:07.070 --> 08:08.529
and not eat
anything at all.

08:08.529 --> 08:09.948
Oh, you know me
so well.

08:09.948 --> 08:11.992
Ooh, oh.

08:13.285 --> 08:16.204
I'll just, uh...

08:16.204 --> 08:18.206
It's all right.
It's just, uh...

08:18.206 --> 08:20.541
Just a little spill.
There's lots left.

08:22.085 --> 08:23.920
Looks delicious.

08:23.920 --> 08:25.464
Yes. Well...

08:25.464 --> 08:27.674
[♪♪♪]

08:28.967 --> 08:30.635
Enjoy.

08:30.635 --> 08:32.553
LEE:
Mm.

08:32.553 --> 08:34.139
Oh, uh, thank you.

08:42.189 --> 08:45.400
[GRIMACES, SIGHS]

08:49.029 --> 08:50.989
[♪♪♪]

08:50.989 --> 08:52.115
[DOOR OPENS]

08:52.115 --> 08:53.658
GIRL:
Sheriff Avery?

08:53.658 --> 08:55.202
Can I help you?

08:55.202 --> 08:56.995
I wanted
to report something.

08:56.995 --> 08:59.498
[GRUNTS]
What's that?

08:59.498 --> 09:01.875
I got this coat from
one of the donation tables,

09:01.875 --> 09:03.710
and I found
a note in it.

09:08.507 --> 09:11.009
"Lucy," or "Livvy," or...

09:11.009 --> 09:13.970
I couldn't make out
the name, either.

09:13.970 --> 09:16.390
"Your constant laughter
fills my heart.

09:16.390 --> 09:20.810
Never lose the joy you find
in everything around you..."

09:20.810 --> 09:22.229
Whoever this coat
belonged to

09:22.229 --> 09:23.730
might want
that note back.

09:23.730 --> 09:25.606
I don't think so,
otherwise

09:25.606 --> 09:27.359
they wouldn't have
given it away.

09:27.359 --> 09:29.861
No, I found the note
in the lining of the pocket

09:29.861 --> 09:31.029
while I was sewing it.

09:31.029 --> 09:32.780
It fell through a hole.

09:32.780 --> 09:34.741
Well, Laura,
I'm not really sure

09:34.741 --> 09:36.451
what you want me
to do with this.

09:36.451 --> 09:39.162
I was thinking you could
help me find who the owner was.

09:39.162 --> 09:40.830
I have more important
things to do

09:40.830 --> 09:42.832
than track down
the owner of an old coat.

09:42.832 --> 09:46.420
You had your feet
on the desk when I came in.

09:46.420 --> 09:48.046
Well, looks can be deceiving.

09:48.046 --> 09:49.464
Okay, it's just
I heard you

09:49.464 --> 09:51.174
used to be good
at solving things.

09:51.174 --> 09:53.134
"Used to"?

09:53.134 --> 09:55.470
My title was Chief
Forensic Investigator.

09:55.470 --> 09:57.222
Okay.

09:57.222 --> 09:59.433
[♪♪♪]

10:00.725 --> 10:03.603
Come back tomorrow,
and we'll ask around.

10:11.652 --> 10:13.821
Just a few more steps.

10:13.821 --> 10:16.032
[♪♪♪]

10:18.618 --> 10:21.329
Okay. Now wait here.

10:21.329 --> 10:22.622
And no peeking.

10:22.622 --> 10:24.874
[LAUGHS]

10:29.045 --> 10:31.756
I know you're there, Elizabeth.
I know your perfume.

10:31.756 --> 10:33.633
That was kind of the idea.

10:34.884 --> 10:36.344
You can open your eyes now.

10:40.515 --> 10:42.267
Our first date.

10:42.267 --> 10:43.643
[LAUGHS]

10:44.936 --> 10:46.396
I knew,

10:46.396 --> 10:47.730
even then,

10:47.730 --> 10:50.150
that I wanted
to be your wife.

10:51.526 --> 10:53.487
This is...

10:53.487 --> 10:56.406
y-you are--
I mean, uh...

10:56.406 --> 10:58.325
I know.

11:02.703 --> 11:04.581
Everything's perfect,
Elizabeth.

11:05.873 --> 11:08.168
Abigail made
all the same dishes.

11:08.168 --> 11:09.710
Shall we eat?

11:09.710 --> 11:10.962
Actually...

11:10.962 --> 11:14.090
I wanna change
something tonight.

11:15.300 --> 11:18.261
I wanna dance with my wife
before dinner.

11:18.261 --> 11:20.472
[♪♪♪]

11:28.355 --> 11:30.398
[TENDER BALLAD PLAYING]

11:41.742 --> 11:43.995
I heard
you were in here.

11:43.995 --> 11:46.373
Oh, we were about to have
an early dinner, Mike.

11:46.373 --> 11:47.748
I'm sorry.

11:47.748 --> 11:49.584
I was checking on
some of our timber.

11:49.584 --> 11:51.878
When I rode by your land,
I saw men up there.

11:51.878 --> 11:53.754
Doing what?
I don't know,

11:53.754 --> 11:55.256
but one of 'em
was Mr. Jenkins,

11:55.256 --> 11:58.009
and he looked
very...intense.

11:58.009 --> 12:00.428
[♪♪♪]

12:02.347 --> 12:04.432
[HOOVES CLOPPING]

12:08.436 --> 12:10.689
What's going on?
What are you doing?

12:10.689 --> 12:13.274
Inspecting the property.
For what?

12:13.274 --> 12:14.526
To confirm its value.

12:14.526 --> 12:16.944
Why do you care?
Jack owns the land.

12:16.944 --> 12:18.530
No, the bank
owns the land.

12:18.530 --> 12:20.490
Jack has a loan to
purchase it.

12:20.490 --> 12:21.991
Which I pay
every month.

12:21.991 --> 12:23.535
The bank appreciates that.

12:23.535 --> 12:25.704
Nevertheless, we'll be
exercising our right

12:25.704 --> 12:27.038
to take back the land.

12:27.038 --> 12:28.623
What right?

12:28.623 --> 12:31.125
This land was purchased
with a demand loan.

12:31.125 --> 12:34.295
That authorizes the bank
to recall the loan

12:34.295 --> 12:36.089
at any time,
with seven days' notice.

12:36.089 --> 12:38.550
Why would you take it back
if I'm paying on time?

12:38.550 --> 12:41.010
We have a business to run,
and how we run it

12:41.010 --> 12:42.596
is none of your concern.

12:42.596 --> 12:44.847
The bank has a cash offer
for the land.

12:44.847 --> 12:47.225
His bank needs cash.

12:47.225 --> 12:48.976
Isn't that right,
Mr. Jenkins?

12:48.976 --> 12:50.853
It's all perfectly legal,
I assure you.

12:50.853 --> 12:53.231
Constable Thornton
signed the loan documents,

12:53.231 --> 12:55.149
and the clause
was clearly stated in it.

12:55.149 --> 12:56.901
Here. Read it.
Section 14-D.

12:56.901 --> 12:58.861
I don't care what
your documents say.

12:58.861 --> 13:00.447
We'll fight you.

13:00.447 --> 13:03.157
You can try, of course,
but the law is on our side.

13:03.950 --> 13:05.410
However...

13:05.410 --> 13:07.870
there's still an option
for you to keep the land.

13:07.870 --> 13:09.872
Which is?

13:09.872 --> 13:12.292
Pay off the remaining balance
within seven days.

13:12.292 --> 13:14.085
The bank will release
the title to you.
[SCOFFS]

13:14.085 --> 13:16.421
I don't have
that kind of money.

13:16.421 --> 13:18.632
Perhaps your wife could help.

13:18.632 --> 13:20.550
I understand your family's
very wealthy.

13:20.550 --> 13:22.677
We're not borrowing
from Elizabeth's family.

13:22.677 --> 13:24.053
This is our land,
our fight.

13:24.053 --> 13:26.431
[♪♪♪]

13:26.431 --> 13:27.890
Have it your way.

13:27.890 --> 13:30.518
Seven days, Constable.

13:30.518 --> 13:32.604
Or you forfeit the land.

13:41.362 --> 13:42.656
[♪♪♪]

13:42.656 --> 13:45.241
ELIZABETH [SIGHS]:
It's not fair.

13:46.451 --> 13:47.910
But Jenkins is right.

13:47.910 --> 13:51.122
[SIGHS]
The bank can take our land.

13:54.250 --> 13:56.002
[SIGHS]

14:00.548 --> 14:03.092
I don't know what to do.

14:07.263 --> 14:08.515
I could...

14:08.515 --> 14:10.057
contact my father.

14:10.057 --> 14:12.644
No. I'd rather lose the land
than go to your father.

14:12.644 --> 14:14.270
Jack.
He was concerned that I

14:14.270 --> 14:16.648
couldn't provide.
A few days into our marriage,

14:16.648 --> 14:19.275
I'm not gonna prove him right.
You wouldn't be.

14:19.275 --> 14:22.069
He would just lend us the money,
then we pay him back.

14:22.069 --> 14:23.363
I'm not gonna do that.

14:27.074 --> 14:28.827
[♪♪♪]

14:28.827 --> 14:30.704
But I promise
you this:

14:30.704 --> 14:33.998
I will build you a house.

14:33.998 --> 14:37.293
It may not be on that land,
but we'll have a house.

14:37.293 --> 14:39.462
We're a family.

14:39.462 --> 14:42.340
We're gonna
see this through as one.

14:51.891 --> 14:54.477
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

14:54.477 --> 14:57.021
I have a blueberry scone
fresh from the oven.

14:57.021 --> 14:58.773
My favorite.

14:58.773 --> 15:01.609
That's the idea.
What are you working on?

15:01.609 --> 15:03.486
My Sunday sermon.

15:03.486 --> 15:06.113
Oh. Well, be prepared
for a packed church.

15:06.113 --> 15:08.241
We missed your service
while you were away.

15:08.241 --> 15:10.827
Oh, no pressure.
[CHUCKLES]

15:10.827 --> 15:12.286
What do you have so far?

15:14.205 --> 15:16.374
"Do nothing
out of selfish ambition

15:16.374 --> 15:19.001
"or vain conceit.
Rather, in humility,

15:19.001 --> 15:21.087
value others
above yourselves."

15:21.087 --> 15:23.297
That's one of
my favorite verses.

15:23.297 --> 15:25.842
I want this week's sermon

15:25.842 --> 15:29.136
to be about taking care of those
who need help the most.

15:30.471 --> 15:32.724
Well, volunteering at
the Children's Hospital,

15:32.724 --> 15:35.643
it's pretty obvious
you live by those words.

15:35.643 --> 15:40.022
Honestly, I...I feel like
I haven't done enough.

15:41.107 --> 15:42.191
Frank...

15:43.484 --> 15:44.736
Your humility

15:44.736 --> 15:47.447
is an inspiration
to us all.

15:47.447 --> 15:49.657
[♪♪♪]

15:55.538 --> 15:57.123
ELIZABETH:
All right, everyone,

15:57.123 --> 15:59.709
these are your vocabulary words
for the week.

15:59.709 --> 16:02.044
Why don't you write them
down in your notebooks?

16:02.044 --> 16:04.672
For homework, I want you
to define each word,

16:04.672 --> 16:07.007
and then use each word
in a sentence.

16:07.007 --> 16:09.761
Yes, Opal?
Those look hard.

16:09.761 --> 16:12.472
Well, yes, they are difficult,
but that's how we learn,

16:12.472 --> 16:14.766
and you can use
your dictionary to help you.

16:18.227 --> 16:20.939
Philip?
Would you like to move closer?

16:21.815 --> 16:23.316
I'm okay.

16:23.316 --> 16:25.359
Please, move up.
You can move back

16:25.359 --> 16:27.695
as soon as you finish
writing down the words.

16:33.827 --> 16:34.994
Is that any better?

16:34.994 --> 16:36.746
Not really.

16:36.746 --> 16:38.289
It's still a little blurry.

16:38.289 --> 16:40.500
I can't tell
what the third word is.

16:40.500 --> 16:42.168
Sur...

16:43.544 --> 16:45.129
S-Sur...prise?

16:45.129 --> 16:47.340
Actually,
it's "support".

16:49.634 --> 16:52.470
How long have you been having
trouble reading the board?

16:52.470 --> 16:54.054
A few days.

16:54.054 --> 16:57.099
Then I think a trip to see
Dr. Shepherd is in order.

16:57.099 --> 16:58.810
Is your father
still out of town?

16:58.810 --> 17:00.561
I'm still staying
with Mrs. Brayman.

17:00.561 --> 17:03.356
In that case, I will take you,
today after school.

17:03.356 --> 17:05.358
But am I sick?

17:05.358 --> 17:07.902
I don't think so.

17:09.863 --> 17:12.072
[♪♪♪]

17:15.284 --> 17:17.328
Afternoon, Abigail.

17:17.328 --> 17:18.538
Henry.

17:18.538 --> 17:21.499
I'll, uh, take
a scone to go.

17:21.499 --> 17:24.043
Is everything okay?
You look like someone

17:24.043 --> 17:26.045
who's about to deliver
a death sentence.

17:26.045 --> 17:28.506
Well, not
a death sentence,

17:28.506 --> 17:31.133
but not exactly
a reprieve, either.

17:31.133 --> 17:32.802
You remember
that I told you

17:32.802 --> 17:35.429
that it'd be hard to find
an investor for the bank.

17:35.429 --> 17:37.640
The one in Union City?

17:37.640 --> 17:39.684
No. Not interested.

17:39.684 --> 17:41.394
How about Silver Lakes?

17:41.394 --> 17:43.521
Nope.

17:43.521 --> 17:45.815
Now, I have
another card up my sleeve,

17:45.815 --> 17:47.942
but, uh...
it's a long shot.

17:47.942 --> 17:50.277
Well, at this point,
I'll take any shot.

17:50.277 --> 17:51.988
All right.

17:51.988 --> 17:53.698
Thank you.

17:55.533 --> 17:56.951
Mrs. Blakeley.

17:56.951 --> 17:58.703
Mr. Gowen.

17:58.703 --> 18:00.580
Florence.

18:00.580 --> 18:02.040
I've heard the rumors.

18:02.040 --> 18:03.332
It's true, isn't it?

18:03.332 --> 18:04.709
What do you mean?

18:04.709 --> 18:06.210
You've put
our financial future

18:06.210 --> 18:08.046
in the hands
of a convicted felon.

18:08.046 --> 18:09.839
Someone who
stole from us!

18:09.839 --> 18:10.840
Florence...

18:10.840 --> 18:12.884
come with me.

18:12.884 --> 18:15.094
[♪♪♪]

18:17.555 --> 18:19.599
I'm trying to keep
our bank afloat.

18:19.599 --> 18:21.225
It's not working.

18:21.225 --> 18:22.769
What are we gonna do?

18:22.769 --> 18:24.854
We can't keep
living this way.

18:24.854 --> 18:25.897
We're not giving up.

18:25.897 --> 18:27.815
[SIGHS]
What does that mean?

18:27.815 --> 18:29.108
That's not gonna stop us

18:29.108 --> 18:30.777
from losing everything,
Abigail.

18:30.777 --> 18:33.780
That is the only thing
that will stop it.

18:33.780 --> 18:35.073
Florence,

18:35.073 --> 18:36.616
we've been
through hard times,

18:36.616 --> 18:38.618
but we've stuck together.

18:38.618 --> 18:42.162
We found a way,
and we'll do it again.

18:45.792 --> 18:47.209
I'm sorry.

18:47.209 --> 18:48.836
Oh...

18:50.296 --> 18:51.839
I understand.

18:51.839 --> 18:53.340
[SIGHS HEAVILY]

18:54.592 --> 18:56.970
[SIGHS]

18:56.970 --> 18:58.846
Ever seen this note
or coat?

18:58.846 --> 19:01.599
No? Okay.
Thank you.

19:01.599 --> 19:05.603
Take that. Come on.
Let's go back inside.

19:15.113 --> 19:17.031
Sorry. I tried.

19:17.031 --> 19:20.242
Is that all Chief
Forensic Investigators do?

19:20.242 --> 19:21.577
Ask around?

19:21.577 --> 19:24.413
No, when it's a serious crime,
we dig deep,

19:24.413 --> 19:26.248
but we're talking
about a coat here.

19:26.248 --> 19:28.042
This could be
important to somebody.

19:28.042 --> 19:29.502
I'm sure it's not.

19:29.502 --> 19:31.129
How can you be sure?

19:31.129 --> 19:32.713
Well, because
it's not a deed,

19:32.713 --> 19:35.174
and it's not a will,
and it's not a treasure map.

19:35.174 --> 19:37.093
It's just
a little note.

19:37.093 --> 19:39.137
[EXHALES SHARPLY]

19:39.137 --> 19:41.514
[♪♪♪]

19:41.514 --> 19:42.598
Wait a minute.

19:44.100 --> 19:45.601
Bring that back to me.

19:45.601 --> 19:47.478
And take the coat off.

19:47.478 --> 19:49.689
[♪♪♪]

19:54.735 --> 19:56.904
The first thing we know
is that...

19:56.904 --> 19:59.365
it wasn't mailed,
it was handed to her,

19:59.365 --> 20:01.492
because it's not signed.

20:01.492 --> 20:03.744
Whoever gave the note
or got the note

20:03.744 --> 20:06.122
had dirty hands.

20:06.122 --> 20:07.748
Is that important?

20:07.748 --> 20:10.209
You never know with clues.

20:15.715 --> 20:18.217
Couldn't you have just gotten
a different coat?

20:20.219 --> 20:22.055
You looking
for more clues?

20:22.055 --> 20:25.016
That's what Chief Forensic
Investigators do.

20:26.726 --> 20:28.435
You look like
Sherlock Holmes.

20:28.435 --> 20:30.521
Except Sherlock Holmes
is make-believe.

20:30.521 --> 20:32.606
I'm the real deal.

20:38.696 --> 20:40.073
What's that?

20:40.073 --> 20:43.325
We're looking for someone
with red hair.

20:43.325 --> 20:45.536
[♪♪♪]

20:48.122 --> 20:50.791
CARSON:
Okay, can you read
this line for me?

20:50.791 --> 20:53.627
S, C, U, T, I, J?

20:53.627 --> 20:55.421
Perfect.
Well done, Philip.

20:55.421 --> 20:58.632
Now, cover your other eye,
and let's read the same line.

21:01.052 --> 21:02.469
T...

21:02.469 --> 21:04.889
O... V...

21:04.889 --> 21:07.641
P... I... T?

21:07.641 --> 21:09.102
Ah.

21:09.102 --> 21:11.979
I think we know
what's going on here, young man.

21:11.979 --> 21:13.272
We do?

21:13.272 --> 21:15.233
Yes. You need glasses.

21:15.233 --> 21:17.317
[♪♪♪]

21:20.113 --> 21:22.656
Let's try these ones.

21:25.952 --> 21:27.327
There you go.

21:27.327 --> 21:30.081
Okay. Now...

21:30.081 --> 21:32.583
Try and read that exact
same line, right there.

21:33.626 --> 21:35.669
S, C, U, T, I, J.

21:35.669 --> 21:38.214
Great. And the line
right underneath?

21:39.590 --> 21:41.550
T, H, L, S, D, A.

21:41.550 --> 21:43.844
Look at that.
I think we have a match.

21:43.844 --> 21:45.596
[CHUCKLES]

21:45.596 --> 21:48.182
But I don't wanna
wear glasses.

21:48.182 --> 21:51.310
Your eyesight is fine
to see things close up.

21:51.310 --> 21:53.896
You only need these
to see things that are far away.

21:53.896 --> 21:56.232
Exactly.
Like the chalkboard,

21:56.232 --> 21:59.068
or when you're standing in
the outfield, playing baseball.

21:59.068 --> 22:01.154
So I won't miss
any more fly balls?

22:01.154 --> 22:03.823
[LAUGHS]
Probably not.

22:03.823 --> 22:06.533
As long as you're
wearing your glasses.

22:11.747 --> 22:13.958
[♪♪♪]

22:15.459 --> 22:17.211
This is so sweet,

22:17.211 --> 22:19.046
but I've never owned
that coat before.

22:19.046 --> 22:20.547
The Sheriff found
a red hair.

22:20.547 --> 22:22.175
But it's not mine.

22:22.175 --> 22:24.718
And this appears to be
written to someone named...

22:24.718 --> 22:26.220
is it Lucy?

22:26.220 --> 22:28.514
Did you ever know anyone
named Lucy or Livvy,

22:28.514 --> 22:30.016
or anyone with that name?

22:30.016 --> 22:32.059
Doesn't ring a bell.
I'm sorry.

22:32.059 --> 22:34.228
Thank you.

22:34.854 --> 22:36.480
Now what?

22:36.480 --> 22:37.815
We keep looking for clues.

22:37.815 --> 22:39.441
Come on.

22:39.441 --> 22:42.320
ELIZABETH [SIGHS]:
You must be glad to have
Frank back.

22:42.320 --> 22:44.989
Oh, sometimes, you don't know
how much you miss someone

22:44.989 --> 22:46.657
until they come home.
Mmm.

22:46.657 --> 22:48.993
We've all missed
his presence in town.

22:48.993 --> 22:51.078
I'm not sure
he's all here.

22:51.078 --> 22:53.122
What do you mean?

22:53.122 --> 22:54.290
He won't say it,

22:54.290 --> 22:56.209
but I know how much
those children

22:56.209 --> 22:57.877
and his work mean to him.

22:57.877 --> 23:00.462
And I know how much
you mean to him.

23:00.462 --> 23:04.967
I know a part of him
wants to be here, but...

23:04.967 --> 23:07.303
only a part of him.

23:07.303 --> 23:10.472
For now...he's here.

23:11.473 --> 23:13.059
You're right,
and for that,

23:13.059 --> 23:14.935
I should be grateful.
Mm-hmm.

23:14.935 --> 23:16.603
Where is Jack?

23:16.603 --> 23:18.356
Oh, wait.
Let me guess.

23:18.356 --> 23:20.274
Up at that land,
getting ready to build

23:20.274 --> 23:22.318
that big, beautiful
house of yours.

23:22.318 --> 23:23.986
About that...

23:23.986 --> 23:25.571
What is it?

23:25.571 --> 23:28.199
Mr. Jenkins...
Oh, no.

23:28.199 --> 23:29.742
What has he done now?

23:29.742 --> 23:31.744
He's taking Jack's land back.

23:31.744 --> 23:34.330
What?
He has a cash buyer for it.

23:34.330 --> 23:36.874
But he can't do that.
He has an agreement with Jack.

23:36.874 --> 23:39.377
Well, we looked at
the loan document, and he can.

23:39.377 --> 23:41.461
What are you gonna do?

23:43.381 --> 23:45.258
We're going to survive.

23:45.258 --> 23:46.175
For better or worse.

23:46.175 --> 23:48.386
[♪♪♪]

23:52.723 --> 23:54.141
Morning.
Morning.

23:54.141 --> 23:55.935
ELIZABETH:
Hi!

23:57.978 --> 23:59.813
Hey, when did
you get glasses?

23:59.813 --> 24:01.232
Yesterday.

24:01.232 --> 24:03.276
But I don't have
to wear them all the time.

24:03.276 --> 24:05.861
ROBERT::
But when you do,
you'll have four eyes.

24:05.861 --> 24:07.405
They kinda
look funny on you.

24:07.405 --> 24:09.782
All right, that's enough.
We don't make fun

24:09.782 --> 24:11.617
of our friends,
we support them.

24:11.617 --> 24:13.744
Which is a word you should
be familiar with,

24:13.744 --> 24:16.830
since it's one of our
vocabulary words this week.

24:17.664 --> 24:19.750
[♪♪♪]

24:20.542 --> 24:22.628
[CHILDREN CHATTERING]

24:28.717 --> 24:30.844
[CHILDREN LAUGHING]

24:34.348 --> 24:37.143
ELIZABETH:
Cody, Robert, you'll be
staying in at recess.

24:37.143 --> 24:38.852
CODY: Aww.
ELIZABETH: If you had to

24:38.852 --> 24:41.188
wear glasses, would it
feel good to be teased?

24:41.188 --> 24:42.898
No.

24:42.898 --> 24:45.567
I want you both
to apologize to Philip.

24:45.567 --> 24:48.737
Sorry.
Sorry.

24:51.073 --> 24:53.491
I think you look very handsome
in your glasses.

24:53.491 --> 24:55.369
I like
your glasses too.

24:55.369 --> 24:57.330
Thanks, Opal.

24:59.665 --> 25:01.875
[♪♪♪]

25:03.543 --> 25:05.796
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

25:06.964 --> 25:09.258
Good morning,
sweetheart.

25:09.258 --> 25:11.344
Good morning.

25:11.344 --> 25:13.012
Whatcha reading there?

25:13.012 --> 25:16.182
Oh, just
a history book.

25:16.182 --> 25:19.685
Yellowed pages
of bygone days.

25:19.685 --> 25:22.688
Not really
relevant anymore.

25:23.647 --> 25:25.232
Breakfast is a little cold.

25:25.232 --> 25:29.195
Yes. It's terrible
when things go cold.

25:29.195 --> 25:30.737
Isn't it?
It is...

25:30.737 --> 25:33.282
but how did it
get ice-cold?

25:33.282 --> 25:34.992
Yes.

25:34.992 --> 25:36.327
How?

25:37.370 --> 25:39.246
Um, I think
I'm just gonna get

25:39.246 --> 25:41.374
a scone and a coffee
at Abigail's.

25:41.374 --> 25:43.876
If you must.

25:45.378 --> 25:46.795
Mm...

25:46.795 --> 25:49.006
I don't supposed you packed
me a lunch, then?

25:49.006 --> 25:51.509
You never notice what
I pack in your lunch anyway.

25:51.509 --> 25:52.843
That's not true.

25:52.843 --> 25:54.594
You made me
that delicious soup.

25:54.594 --> 25:56.763
Lunch isn't always
about food,

25:56.763 --> 25:58.349
Lee.

25:58.349 --> 25:59.892
Right.

25:59.892 --> 26:03.561
Okay, well, I will, uh,
see you at dinnertime, then.

26:04.771 --> 26:07.066
[DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

26:08.901 --> 26:11.445
ELIZABETH:
I have to say,
I am very impressed

26:11.445 --> 26:13.030
with your scores
on these tests.

26:13.030 --> 26:15.074
It's clear you
all studied very hard.

26:15.074 --> 26:16.367
I got an A-plus!

26:16.367 --> 26:18.118
And since you all
did so well,

26:18.118 --> 26:21.121
I'm going to give you an extra
five minutes at recess today!

26:21.121 --> 26:22.415
Class dismissed.

26:22.415 --> 26:24.291
[CHILDREN CHATTERING]

26:24.291 --> 26:26.377
Don't you want
to come play baseball?

26:26.377 --> 26:29.380
Now you have glasses, you'll
be able to catch the ball.

26:29.380 --> 26:32.341
I don't feel too good.
I think I'll stay inside.

26:35.052 --> 26:37.263
[♪♪♪]

26:38.596 --> 26:40.849
Philip, have you
been crying again?

26:40.849 --> 26:41.934
No.

26:41.934 --> 26:43.185
Are you sure?

26:43.185 --> 26:44.311
I promise.

26:44.311 --> 26:47.106
But my head
has been hurting,

26:47.106 --> 26:48.815
and my eyes hurt, too.

26:48.815 --> 26:51.569
Sometimes that can happen
when you start wearing glasses.

26:51.569 --> 26:53.237
But they're helping me
see better.

26:53.237 --> 26:56.073
I know, and I'm very proud
of you for wearing them,

26:56.073 --> 26:57.783
but your lenses
might be too strong.

26:57.783 --> 27:00.327
I'll take you back to see
Dr. Shepherd today, okay?

27:00.327 --> 27:01.912
Okay.
And in the meantime,

27:01.912 --> 27:03.747
I'll get you a cold towel
to help your headache.

27:03.747 --> 27:05.291
Thank you, Mrs. Thornton.

27:05.291 --> 27:07.501
[♪♪♪]

27:19.305 --> 27:20.389
Mr. Jenkins.

27:22.182 --> 27:23.809
Mrs. Stanton.

27:23.809 --> 27:26.145
You're calling in
Jack's loan?

27:26.145 --> 27:27.938
It's all perfectly legal.

27:27.938 --> 27:30.357
[SCOFFS]
There's what's legal
and what's right,

27:30.357 --> 27:31.609
and that's not right.

27:31.609 --> 27:33.777
There's a buyer
for that land in Buxton,

27:33.777 --> 27:35.362
and the bank needs cash.

27:35.362 --> 27:36.863
Your bank needs me.

27:36.863 --> 27:39.199
I'm trying to find investors
to keep you afloat.

27:39.199 --> 27:41.034
As are we.
Well, until that happens,

27:41.034 --> 27:43.120
let's be honorable
and not underhanded.

27:45.205 --> 27:47.374
I'll take that
under consideration,

27:47.374 --> 27:48.666
but I make no promises.

27:51.669 --> 27:53.713
Make this go away,
Mr. Jenkins.

27:53.713 --> 27:55.924
[♪♪♪]

28:02.181 --> 28:05.643
CARSON:
Do these headaches come on when
you're wearing your glasses?

28:05.643 --> 28:07.520
Nope. I get them a lot,

28:07.520 --> 28:09.396
even when I don't have
the glasses on.

28:09.396 --> 28:12.191
Philip...why didn't
you tell us that sooner?

28:12.191 --> 28:14.568
I didn't want anyone
to be mad at me.

28:14.568 --> 28:17.737
Oh. Sweetheart,
we could never be mad

28:17.737 --> 28:19.031
about you
not feeling well.

28:19.031 --> 28:20.991
And is your vision
still a little blurry,

28:20.991 --> 28:22.951
even when you're
wearing your glasses?

28:22.951 --> 28:24.077
Sometimes.

28:24.786 --> 28:26.205
Okay.

28:26.205 --> 28:28.457
We're gonna try something
totally different.

28:28.457 --> 28:29.833
Keep looking at me

28:29.833 --> 28:31.210
and tell me,

28:31.210 --> 28:34.004
how many fingers
am I holding up?

28:34.004 --> 28:36.298
I-I can't really
see your hand there.

28:36.298 --> 28:37.924
Okay.

28:37.924 --> 28:39.009
Now how many here?

28:39.009 --> 28:40.553
Two.

28:40.553 --> 28:42.680
Excellent.
And on this side?

28:42.680 --> 28:44.931
I can't really
see your hand there, either.

28:44.931 --> 28:47.434
Okay.
You hang tight here, buddy.

28:47.434 --> 28:49.353
Okay?
We'll be right back.

28:49.353 --> 28:51.564
[♪♪♪]

28:52.981 --> 28:55.317
Carson...
what's going on?

28:55.317 --> 28:57.986
This is a lot more serious
than I first thought.

28:57.986 --> 28:59.779
I think Philip has glaucoma.

28:59.779 --> 29:01.490
What's that?
It's an eye disease

29:01.490 --> 29:03.659
that damages the optic
nerve in the brain.

29:03.659 --> 29:05.285
Builds up fluid in the eye,

29:05.285 --> 29:07.954
puts pressure on the nerve,
causes the eyes to water.

29:07.954 --> 29:10.249
So that's why Philip
looked like he was crying.

29:10.249 --> 29:13.210
Glaucoma also blurs
the peripheral vision,

29:13.210 --> 29:15.045
which is why
he couldn't see my hand.

29:15.045 --> 29:17.464
Oh, no.
Is he gonna be all right?

29:17.464 --> 29:20.467
Without the proper treatment,
he could lose his eyesight.

29:20.467 --> 29:22.761
Carson...

29:22.761 --> 29:24.012
we can't let that happen.

29:24.012 --> 29:25.180
Of course not.

29:25.180 --> 29:27.140
But I'm not
an ophthalmologist.

29:27.140 --> 29:28.850
Philip needs
to see a specialist

29:28.850 --> 29:30.769
at the Children's Hospital
right away.

29:30.769 --> 29:32.479
I'll send a telegram
to his father.

29:32.479 --> 29:34.231
He's been working outside
Cape Fullerton

29:34.231 --> 29:35.649
for the past few months.

29:35.649 --> 29:37.067
He should know.

29:37.067 --> 29:39.278
[♪♪♪]

29:42.822 --> 29:45.200
[♪♪♪]

29:45.200 --> 29:47.578
ABIGAIL:
So you're saying
glaucoma is treatable?

29:47.578 --> 29:49.121
So Philip
won't go blind?

29:49.121 --> 29:51.039
His eyesight
can be saved,

29:51.039 --> 29:53.125
but he's going to need
surgery right away.

29:53.125 --> 29:55.711
It's a very
delicate procedure

29:55.711 --> 29:58.380
that needs to be performed
by an ophthalmologist.

29:58.380 --> 30:00.674
You must know someone
at Children's Hospital.

30:00.674 --> 30:02.301
Can you help us?

30:03.343 --> 30:04.928
I do know
the administrators.

30:04.928 --> 30:07.264
Maybe if I explain
the situation,

30:07.264 --> 30:09.642
they can find Philip a bed.

30:09.642 --> 30:11.685
I'll go send
a telegram right now.

30:11.685 --> 30:13.646
I really
appreciate it, Frank.

30:14.521 --> 30:16.189
I'll be right back.

30:16.189 --> 30:17.816
I'll go with you.

30:26.908 --> 30:30.496
It would be devastating
if Philip went blind.

30:30.496 --> 30:32.623
Elizabeth,
don't you worry.

30:32.623 --> 30:34.207
Frank will move
heaven and Earth

30:34.207 --> 30:35.959
for Philip
to get the help he needs.

30:35.959 --> 30:38.170
[♪♪♪]

30:48.347 --> 30:50.265
[ENGINE SHUTS OFF]

31:00.859 --> 31:02.528
Hi, sweetheart.

31:04.070 --> 31:05.864
Hello.

31:05.864 --> 31:07.407
Listen...

31:07.407 --> 31:11.286
I know that you've been feeling
a little blue lately,

31:11.286 --> 31:12.705
so...

31:12.705 --> 31:14.080
I have a surprise for you.

31:14.914 --> 31:15.915
You do?

31:15.915 --> 31:17.626
Mm-hmm.
What?

31:17.626 --> 31:19.628
Come here.

31:22.005 --> 31:24.216
[♪♪♪]

31:26.552 --> 31:28.220
Oh, Lee.

31:28.220 --> 31:31.515
[CHUCKLES]
You didn't have to go
to all this trouble.

31:31.515 --> 31:33.642
Oh, I think
maybe I did.

31:33.642 --> 31:35.561
And there's more.

31:41.233 --> 31:43.235
Open it.

31:43.235 --> 31:44.695
I know what
it says, Lee.

31:44.695 --> 31:46.196
I wrote it.

31:46.196 --> 31:47.781
Open it.

31:51.117 --> 31:52.619
It's the original
Broadway cast.

31:52.619 --> 31:54.872
Gilbert and Sullivan's
"Pirates of Penzance"

31:54.872 --> 31:56.456
and the New York
Touring Company.

31:56.456 --> 31:59.334
You are the love of my life,
Rosemary.

31:59.334 --> 32:02.254
[LAUGHING]
Oh, Lee!

32:06.717 --> 32:07.760
A toast.

32:09.010 --> 32:11.096
[GASPS]

32:13.724 --> 32:15.975
To married life.

32:15.975 --> 32:17.269
[CLINKS]

32:17.269 --> 32:19.229
To being
married to you.

32:24.067 --> 32:26.278
[♪♪♪]

32:27.487 --> 32:29.406
You see that little
smudge down there?

32:29.406 --> 32:31.116
I think it might
be coal dust.

32:31.116 --> 32:33.285
That does look like it.
I know your husband

32:33.285 --> 32:35.203
was a supervisor
in the old mine.

32:35.203 --> 32:37.414
I just thought you
might have some idea.

32:37.414 --> 32:39.207
I don't recognize the coat.

32:39.207 --> 32:41.167
We think the person
might have red hair,

32:41.167 --> 32:43.211
but we've already
asked Mrs. Sullivan.

32:44.379 --> 32:48.425
You recognize the name
Livvy or Lucy?

32:48.425 --> 32:50.594
No. I'm sorry.

32:50.594 --> 32:52.304
Thanks anyway,
Mrs. Stanton.

32:52.304 --> 32:54.055
Good luck.

32:55.891 --> 32:57.267
Wait.

32:57.267 --> 32:59.812
The name on the note--
it's not Lucy or Livvy.

32:59.812 --> 33:01.062
It's "Lovey."

33:01.062 --> 33:02.397
Lovey?

33:02.397 --> 33:04.023
It was a nickname,

33:04.023 --> 33:06.025
and she's not the one
with red hair.

33:06.025 --> 33:08.987
It was her husband.

33:08.987 --> 33:10.614
[CHUCKLES]

33:10.614 --> 33:12.616
[♪♪♪]

33:14.159 --> 33:15.661
Florence!

33:15.661 --> 33:16.912
Hold on a second!

33:16.912 --> 33:18.455
Oh! Laura!

33:18.455 --> 33:20.916
Oh, my old coat
looks good on you.

33:20.916 --> 33:22.208
We found this note

33:22.208 --> 33:24.002
in the lining
of the coat.

33:28.966 --> 33:30.425
"Lovey...

33:30.425 --> 33:33.637
"Your constant laughter
fills my heart.

33:33.637 --> 33:37.098
Never lose the joy you find
in everything around you."

33:37.098 --> 33:38.308
[GASPS]

33:38.308 --> 33:40.435
[TEARFULLY]
Oh...

33:41.645 --> 33:44.564
I...I was 16
when Paul gave this to me.

33:44.564 --> 33:46.232
My childhood sweetheart.

33:46.232 --> 33:48.443
My husband.

33:50.362 --> 33:53.866
You know, I had forgotten
what he saw in me...

33:54.908 --> 33:56.535
How I used to be...

33:56.535 --> 33:58.286
It was all her.

33:59.245 --> 34:02.081
Thank you so much for this.

34:02.081 --> 34:05.293
It means the world to me.

34:05.293 --> 34:06.545
I will treasure it.

34:06.545 --> 34:07.713
Thank you for the coat.

34:07.713 --> 34:09.965
Oh, you're so welcome.

34:09.965 --> 34:11.174
Thank you.

34:11.174 --> 34:12.551
You're welcome.

34:13.259 --> 34:14.469
Oh.

34:16.471 --> 34:18.807
Well done.

34:19.766 --> 34:21.977
[♪♪♪]

34:40.954 --> 34:42.664
Jack.

34:45.876 --> 34:47.920
[♪♪♪]

34:47.920 --> 34:49.337
What's the matter?

34:49.337 --> 34:51.089
I've been...

34:51.089 --> 34:52.632
[SIGHS]

34:52.632 --> 34:54.927
I've been given
an assignment at Fort Clay.

34:59.681 --> 35:01.099
You're leaving again?

35:01.099 --> 35:03.142
Only for two months.

35:04.352 --> 35:05.771
It's to train
other Mounties,

35:05.771 --> 35:07.814
it's considered
a prestigious assignment,

35:07.814 --> 35:09.649
an honor, actually.

35:10.734 --> 35:12.402
I thought we were done
with that.

35:12.402 --> 35:13.904
We almost are,
I promise you.

35:15.154 --> 35:17.323
I've been worrying
about you for so long--

35:17.323 --> 35:18.450
This is different.

35:18.450 --> 35:19.952
There's no danger.

35:19.952 --> 35:22.120
The worst that can happen
is I lose my voice

35:22.120 --> 35:24.205
yelling at
the new recruits.

35:26.041 --> 35:28.043
I don't see you
as much of a yeller.

35:28.043 --> 35:30.045
More like
a stern lecturer.

35:33.966 --> 35:35.592
The thing is,

35:35.592 --> 35:37.427
we can't go
to Chicago right now.

35:42.057 --> 35:43.349
Then I'll go with you.

35:44.810 --> 35:45.852
To Fort Clay?

35:45.852 --> 35:48.063
Mm-hmm.

35:49.606 --> 35:52.317
[SIGHS]
You can't leave
Hope Valley for two months.

35:52.317 --> 35:55.445
I can for as long as it takes us
to get to Fort Clay and back.

35:55.445 --> 35:58.406
We'll consider it
our honeymoon.

35:58.406 --> 36:00.700
I hear it's beautiful country.

36:00.700 --> 36:03.078
It's beautiful...

36:03.078 --> 36:06.205
intelligent,
and understanding.

36:07.415 --> 36:08.917
Now, how'd I get so lucky?

36:11.795 --> 36:15.507
They say each of us
is born under a star.

36:16.842 --> 36:18.927
Ours aren't just lucky...

36:18.927 --> 36:20.887
they're charmed.

36:20.887 --> 36:23.098
[♪♪♪]

36:29.980 --> 36:32.231
[♪♪♪]

36:33.483 --> 36:35.234
Don't worry.
The doctors are gonna

36:35.234 --> 36:37.236
take good care of you
once you get there.

36:37.236 --> 36:40.073
And Pastor Frank's gonna
make sure you get there safely.

36:40.073 --> 36:41.574
Okay?

36:43.910 --> 36:45.203
Thank you, Frank.

36:45.203 --> 36:47.413
I don't want you
to worry about a thing.

36:47.413 --> 36:49.041
You told my dad
where I'm going?

36:49.041 --> 36:51.501
I did. He'll be waiting
for you in Cape Fullerton,

36:51.501 --> 36:53.962
and we'll see you back here
before you know it.

36:53.962 --> 36:56.255
Promise?
I promise.

36:56.255 --> 36:57.382
I'll miss you.

36:57.382 --> 36:59.676
I will miss you too.

36:59.676 --> 37:01.887
[♪♪♪]

37:07.100 --> 37:09.227
We're sorry
we teased you, Philip.

37:09.227 --> 37:10.729
We didn't mean
anything by it.

37:10.729 --> 37:12.230
That's okay.

37:12.230 --> 37:13.356
This is for you.

37:13.356 --> 37:15.358
It's from
the whole class.

37:19.278 --> 37:20.864
Laura drew the picture.

37:20.864 --> 37:22.032
And we all signed it.

37:22.032 --> 37:24.283
It's really nice.

37:25.952 --> 37:27.245
Thanks.

37:27.245 --> 37:28.538
LAURA:
Goodbye, Philip.

37:28.538 --> 37:29.831
See you soon.

37:29.831 --> 37:32.209
Get well.
We're gonna miss you.

37:33.292 --> 37:35.336
[CHUCKLING]
Aw.

37:36.963 --> 37:39.591
Abigail...

37:39.591 --> 37:42.468
I need to talk
to you about something.

37:42.468 --> 37:44.930
I know what you have to do.

37:44.930 --> 37:46.431
You do?

37:48.100 --> 37:49.976
You have to stay there,
Frank.

37:51.144 --> 37:53.438
Your devotion
to those children,

37:53.438 --> 37:55.690
it's your calling.

37:57.483 --> 38:00.946
Yeah. It really is.

38:03.281 --> 38:04.866
You're a good man, Frank.

38:08.828 --> 38:10.830
Coming from you,
that means a lot.

38:22.008 --> 38:24.052
I wish I could ask you
to go with me.

38:24.052 --> 38:26.972
I wish I could
ask you to stay.

38:44.948 --> 38:47.033
You take care, Cody.

38:47.033 --> 38:48.618
When will you be back?

38:48.618 --> 38:51.537
Well, I'm not really sure...

38:51.537 --> 38:52.664
but I'll write to you.

38:52.664 --> 38:54.791
Will you
write me back?

38:56.126 --> 38:57.669
You keep listening
to your ma.

38:57.669 --> 38:59.921
You'll be all right.

38:59.921 --> 39:02.632
...Cape Fullerton.
Okay.

39:08.805 --> 39:11.016
[♪♪♪]

39:31.036 --> 39:33.538
What do you think about
camping at Diamond Lake?

39:33.538 --> 39:34.831
I love it.

39:34.831 --> 39:36.415
We can catch
trout for dinner.

39:36.415 --> 39:37.750
Maybe,
but just to be safe,

39:37.750 --> 39:39.961
I packed some tins
of pork and beans.

39:39.961 --> 39:41.838
[LAUGHING]

39:41.838 --> 39:43.006
Jack...

39:43.006 --> 39:44.216
Elizabeth.

39:44.216 --> 39:46.218
Mr. Jenkins, we don't
have your money.

39:46.218 --> 39:47.635
That's not why I'm here.

39:47.635 --> 39:49.179
I'm happy to tell you
the bank

39:49.179 --> 39:50.847
won't be taking
your property.

39:53.599 --> 39:55.727
Well, we're grateful,
of course,

39:55.727 --> 39:58.104
but what's changed?

39:58.104 --> 39:59.605
You just keep up
the payments

39:59.605 --> 40:02.441
and the land will
be all yours soon enough.

40:04.277 --> 40:06.946
[LAUGHS]
What do you think happened?

40:06.946 --> 40:09.157
[♪♪♪]

40:11.993 --> 40:14.871
I have an idea.

40:14.871 --> 40:17.290
Abigail Stanton...

40:17.290 --> 40:20.459
did you say something
to Mr. Jenkins?

40:20.459 --> 40:23.338
Oh, I might have had
a little talk with him.

40:23.338 --> 40:25.464
I'm guessing it wasn't
a very friendly one.

40:25.464 --> 40:27.259
Sometimes people
need to be reminded

40:27.259 --> 40:29.802
how we treat each other
in Hope Valley.

40:29.802 --> 40:32.138
We are very lucky
to have you as mayor.

40:32.138 --> 40:34.266
Well, given
our financial situation,

40:34.266 --> 40:36.726
I don't know that everyone
would agree with you.

40:36.726 --> 40:38.519
And they'd be wrong.

40:38.519 --> 40:40.772
Thank you, Abigail.
Oh.

40:40.772 --> 40:42.982
[♪♪♪]

40:44.150 --> 40:45.360
You're the best,
Abigail.

40:45.360 --> 40:47.320
[CHUCKLES]

40:48.905 --> 40:51.157
Well, you two, go.
Enjoy your honeymoon.

40:51.157 --> 40:53.285
[BOTH LAUGHING]

40:54.827 --> 40:56.079
Abigail.

40:56.079 --> 40:57.914
I've got some good news.

40:57.914 --> 40:59.958
I found a possible investor
for the bank.

40:59.958 --> 41:01.751
She's gonna come to town
next week.

41:01.751 --> 41:03.920
Oh. Thank you, Henry.

41:03.920 --> 41:05.297
Now, I've convinced her

41:05.297 --> 41:07.173
to come and have
a look at the place,

41:07.173 --> 41:09.467
but you'll have to sell her
on the idea.

41:11.010 --> 41:12.804
All right.

41:30.529 --> 41:32.740
[♪♪♪]
